observations.recommendation:
(a) instruct the Municipal Accountant disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the assets/items subject for disposal so as not to misled users thereof;
(b) assign a focal person who will focus on the requirements needed to enable the immediate transfer of title of the subject lands under the name of the Municipality; and
(c) instruct the Disposal Committee to dispose obsolete/unserviceable properties in accordance with prescribed procedures to avoid further deterioration and depreciation thereof.

a. instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for business taxpayers; 
b. direct the BPLO to – 
i. ensure the timely submission of proof of annual gross receipts/income and as well the submission of copies of ITRs on or before April 30 of each year; 
ii. consider hiring personnel to assist in monitoring ITR submissions to ensure accurate assessment and collection of annual business taxes; 
iii. coordinate with the BPLTAS system provider for a review of business tax rates before transitioning to new software; and 
iv. ensure the accuracy of rates in the upcoming system software for input in business permit and licensing; 
c. advise the Acting Municipal Treasurer to – 
i. assign an inspector to every application for business termination, with the responsibility of verifying the operational status by visiting the business address; and 
ii. conduct examination of books of accounts of businessmen after attendance to the relative trainings and seminars related; and 
d. ensure that the Revenue Code is regularly updated, adhering to the provisions of Section 191 of RA 7160, with updates conducted no more frequently than once every five (5) years.

Submit the consolidated PIF to the SA/ATL and the GIF, GSIS not later than April 30 of each year in accordance with COA Circular 2018-002;

Completely filled-out the PIF, data such as property number, market/appraised value/insurable interest, date of appraisal and remarks or other important information related to individual assets shall be provided;

Request the turnover documents from the DPWH for the Evacuation Center (OMDRRMO Building) and Pilar Municipal Building to have a complete ownership of the said buildings; 

Ensure that all serviceable motor vehicles and insurable properties are properly covered with insurance with the GIF of the GSIS to compensate any risk associated with the MGP properties/assets;

Review the insurance coverage of the buildings especially those that are flood free prone to reduce the premium on insurance;

Ensure that all the data presented in the reports are accurate and free from errors to avoid misleading information to intended readers; and 

Attach copy of the insurance policies to the report being submitted to the AT for verification/audit.

Follow strictly the prescribed timeline in the preparation of the annual SEF Budget as provided in DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017;

Require the LSB to prepare the LSB three-year program, supported by approved SIPs and other information from DepEd Regional Office, prior to the preparation and approval of the SEF Budget and furnish the AT for reference and review purposes;

Include allocations for the ECCD program from the SEF budget for each year; 

Adhere to the format presented in SEF Budget Accountability Form No. 1 of the aforementioned JC; and 

Submit religiously the required quarterly and annual Reports on SEF Utilization.

4. Review the property records and reconcile them with the actual inventory count;


5. Reclassify tangible items that were acquired before CY 2023 with a cost of ₱50,000.00 and below to semi-expendable property;


6. Retain the existing Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PAR) issued to end-users which shall serve as the ICS until their accountabilities for such items are extinguished;


7. Issue the corresponding ICS for all semi-expendable property acquired in the ensuing years; and


8. Designate personnel to prepare and maintain the forms, registry and reports prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004, and to timely update them for complete recording, monitoring, and safeguarding of semi-expendable properties.

The Municipality enforces the remedies provided in the Local Government Code such as, but not limited to the following:


24. Prepare a certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one (1) year, and a statement of the reason or reasons for such non-collection or non-payment;


25. Post the said list at the Municipality, in publicly accessible and conspicuous place in each barangay, and/or publish the notice of delinquency in the newspaper of general circulation once a week for two consecutive weeks;


26. Issue notice of delinquency and/or final demand letter to concerned property owner; and


27. Submit to the Sanggunian concerned on or before December 31 of the year immediately succeeding the year in which the delinquencies were incurred, with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
All regular purchases shall be coursed through the inventory account, except those purchased out of the petty cash fund which shall be for immediate use;
The GSO or the property supply/officer shall consolidate weekly the RIS for which supplies and materials were issued using the SSMI and submit the SSMI together with the original copy of the RIS to the Municipal Accountant;
The Municipal Accountant shall prepare the JEV based on the SSMI submitted by the GSO or property/supply officer to record in the appropriate expenditure accounts; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure the correctness of entries and the posting of transactions in the GLs to present the correct amount in the FS.

Nonetheless, we recommended that the PMSB:
Continue to support the SEF Budget with approved SIPs, LSB three-year program and other information from DepEd Regional Office, prior to the preparation and approval of the SEF Budget and furnish the AT for reference and review purposes;
Require the concerned officials to submit the SIP within the prescribed period hence not to affect the preparation of the annual SEF budget;
Follow strictly the prescribed timeline in the preparation of the annual SEF Budget as provided in DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017; and
Ensure that only the allowable expenses shall be charged in the SEF budget in accordance with the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG JMC No. S. 2017 and JCs No. 1 and 2.

Continue to remit promptly their collections in accordance with the prescribed period of remittance;

Continue to prepare the RCD every time they remit their collections to show the actual date of remittance to the OMT; 

Double-check the dates stated in the RCD before submitting the same to the MT; and

Continue to prepare/update their individual cashbooks to monitor properly their collections and AFs.

We also recommended that the LCE direct the MT to continue monitoring and enforcing prompt remittance of collections by revenue collectors to avoid the accumulation of cash and possible loss thereof through theft or misappropriation.

Continue the implementation of PPAs based on the agreed timeline as stated in the MOA; 

In the future, direct the responsible Departments/Offices to expedite the implementation of the unimplemented PPAs thru meticulous planning in order to optimally utilize the readily available funds received from SAs within the agreed timeframe, thus ensuring timely delivery of the intended benefits to constituents; 

Ensure to retain copies of MOA after signing by the LCE, as basis for the utilization of the subject fund transfers, and furnish the AT for proper evaluation and timely verification of the implementation and disbursements made in relation to these trust accounts;  

Continue to comply with the provision of COA Circular No. 94-013 regarding the refund of the excess/unutilized fund to the concerned SA or BTr; and 

Exercise diligence in recording transactions relative to the Due to NGAs account hence to avoid errors that may affect the fairness of presentation of the FS.

Continue to exercise diligence, prudence and proper control in the disposition of the MGP’s funds while limiting expenditures within the total income realized and collected during the year to avoid cash deficiency;

Invest the idle cash in major infrastructure projects or other PPAs that can help improve the livelihood and general welfare of the MGP’s constituents; and

Require the finance committee to prepare a Cash Analysis and submit the same to the LCE as a reference for decision-making purposes.

Coordinate with the PGS to have specific written criteria/guidelines in the selection of the beneficiaries under the 7K programs; 

Include in the MOA as an attachment or as part of the MOA the said criteria or guidelines;

Effect the corrections in the FURs submitted to the PGS by making the necessary adjustments/refunds for erroneous charging/recording of expenses; 

Transfer the amount of ₱716,810.00 to the GF from the counterpart under the 7K program in the TF account; and 

Compel the AO concerned to prepare the RD for partial liquidation of CAs and submit one liquidation report only when the liquidation SDs are complete before the due date of liquidation.  Henceforth, the OMAcc ensures the completeness of SDs for all vouchers before submission to the AT in compliance with the above-mentioned provisions on the grant and liquidation of CAs.

Monitor closely the implementation of the targeted PPAs and the utilization of the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action; 

Conduct timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization; and

The monthly preparation and submission of the report on sources and utilization of the LDRRMF.

The MDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMFIP with a complete list of targeted PPAs to be funded by the LDRRMF current appropriations and updated unexpended prior year fund balances;

The MDRRMO to submit the LDRRMFIP to COA and the concerned department of the LGUs; 

The MA to maintain SLs for the STF per year of transfer;

The MBO to require the submission of Work and Financial Plan and Program of Work for the proposed PPAs;

The MBO to furnish the MA copies of the said documents to facilitate the proper and uniform categorization of appropriations and expenses into MOOE and CO; and

The MA and MBO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records to ensure the correctness of the reported amounts for the appropriation and utilization of the LDRRMF and the amount of unutilized QRF and MF-MOOE to be transferred to the STF.

All requesting units to accomplish properly the PRs and include the specific purpose of the requisition;

The BAC to review the RFQs and Abstract of Quotations and Awards for completeness of vital information;

The Procurement Unit to submit the POs and its SDs within five days from the perfection of the contract to the AT; 

The concerned personnel in charge of inspecting and accepting deliveries of procured items to fill-out completely the AIR and notify the AT of the date and time of scheduled deliveries within 24 hours from acceptance thereof.  Henceforth, liquidated damages for late/delayed deliveries of purchased supplies/goods may be deducted; and

Include the brand names, together with the specifications of the items quoted by the supplier in response to the advertised relevant characteristics and/or performance requirements of the items needed by the agency in the POs to serve as reference during deliveries, inspection and acceptance by Management.

The BAC, the Secretariat, and the TWG to strictly abide by the standards set forth by RA No. 9184, its Revised IRR and other relevant laws on government procurement;  

All concerned officials/employees exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to ensure that all requirements of the procurement law are faithfully adhered to;

The MA shall observe the requirements of COA Circular No. 2012-001 at all times in processing transactions;

The concerned official prepare and submit the detailed engineering certification to the AT;

Ensure that the approved CSHP is submitted before the execution of the contract following the provision of RA No. 9184; 

Ensure the submission of the Results of Test Analysis, if applicable; and

Ensure that all liquidated damages are being collected from the erring contractors.

Require the contractors to take immediate completion/correction of the project based on the provisions of the contracts; otherwise, take appropriate remedies as provided in RA No. 9184 and enforce Section 68 of its RIRR once the liquidated damages reach 10% of the contract price to encourage compliance with the delivery schedules and avoid unnecessary delays;

Reject the services of the contractors who do not adhere to the provisions of RA No. 9184; and

Require the concerned officials to exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties and ensure that all requirements of the procurement law are faithfully adhered to.

We further recommended that the Municipality enforce the remedies provided in the Local Government Code such as, but not limited to the following:

Prepare a certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one (1) year, and a statement of the reason or reasons for such non-collection or non-payment;

Post the said list at the Municipality, in publicly accessible and conspicuous place in each barangay, and/or publish the notice of delinquency in the newspaper of general circulation once a week for two consecutive weeks;

Issue notice of delinquency and/or final demand letter to concerned property owner; and

Submit to the Sanggunian concerned on or before December 31 of the year immediately succeeding the year in which the delinquencies were incurred, with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require Inventory Committee to conduct physical count on 14 PPE accounts totaling ₱426.595 million;
b.	Direct the Accounting and Property Units to reconcile their records to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in the PPELCs and  the Property Cards (PCs) within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee, to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts;
Comply with the uniform property identification system and prominently show in the property sticker the PPEs vital information to include: description of the property, model number, serial number, acquisition date/cost, person accountable, space for the validation/signature of the Inventory Committee; and
Require the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain the PCs to facilitate the required regular reconciliation of the PPE accounts.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and OIC-Municipal Accountant to submit the documents including MOA on fund transfers from NGAs on the prescribed period;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to properly monitor the receipts, documentary requirements and utilization of the fund transfers;
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant  and PESO Focal person to submit the required/relevant documents in the implementation of DOLE Projects  and other project of the Municipality to establish validity of claim; and
Return any unutilized balances to the source agency.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require all Accountable Officers/Collectors to observe daily remittance of their collections intact as prescribed by Section 29 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I to lessen the risk of misuse and loss of funds;
Direct Municipal Treasurer to monitor and control the issuance of Accountable Forms to collectors without sacrificing efficiency.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Review the property records and reconcile them with the actual inventory count;
Reclassify tangible items that were acquired before CY 2023 with a cost of ₱50,000.00 and below to semi-expendable property;
Retain the existing Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PAR) issued to end-users which shall serve as the ICS until their accountabilities for such items are extinguished;
Issue the corresponding ICS for all semi-expendable property acquired in the ensuing years; and
Designate personnel to prepare and maintain the forms, registry and reports prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004, and to timely update them for complete recording, monitoring, and safeguarding of semi-expendable properties.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Direct the OIC Municipal Accountant to submit an approved SB resolution amending the project location of Desilting of Balisong River to include Brgy. San Ramon as one of the locations;

Direct the Municipal Engineer to specify in the Program of Work the dimensions (length, width and thickness) for the expected/accomplished output of the ongoing and future projects;

Utilize the 20% DF in accordance with laws, rules and regulations to attain desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes; and

Observe compliance with the Fundamental Principle that all claims against government funds shall be supported with complete documentation.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:
instruct the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer to reconcile accounting and property records for the correction of verified discrepancies;
assign a focal person who will focus on the requirements needed to facilitate the immediate transfer of title of the subject lands under the name of the Municipality;
instruct the OIC-General Services Officer to –
	direct the personnel assigned in maintenance of property cards to properly and completely fill out the Property Cards and to use the prescribed LRNPC for the Road Networks;
	conduct further investigation on the stolen items and request for relief from accountability, otherwise, the money value of the said stolen items will be paid by the accountable person.; and
instruct the Disposal Committee to dispose obsolete/unserviceable properties in accordance with Section 125 of NGAS Manual Volume I to avoid further deterioration of the property and consequent decrease of its recoverable value.

We recommended that the LCE require:
The OMAss to continue the appraisal and assessment of the existing real properties within the municipality but not oftener than once every three (3) years except in case of new improvements substantially increasing the value of the properties or of any change in actual use.  Hence, the OMAss shall conduct frequent physical inspection or survey of real properties;
The OMT to extend its comprehensive information drive/campaign on tax collection to all barangays.  Also, continue the usual posting and sending out of notices to taxpayers with the help of barangay officials.

We recommended that the LCE require the LSB to:
Coordinate properly with the Office of the Municipal Budget Officer and OMA so that accurate figures will be incorporated in the SEF annual budget.  Henceforth, issue supplemental budget for succeeding collections in excess of estimated budget;
Comply with the required LSB three-year program, supported by approved individual SIPs, prior to the preparation and approval of the SEF Budget and furnish the AT for reference and review purposes;
Support the SEF budget with plan of targeted PPAs to be funded out of the fund presented by allotment class and per school; and
Follow strictly the prescribed timelines in the preparation of the annual SEF Budget as provided in the JC.

We recommended that:

1. The Inventory Committee headed by General Services Officer:

(a) Reconcile property records with accounting records and variance shall be traced and investigated immediately; 
(b) Properly classify asset type in conducting physical count and report the same in the RPCPPE per asset type;
(c) Properly fill out the prescribed RPCPPE format and determine correct unit value per item presented on it.

2. The Municipal Accountant update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card and reconcile PPE account with the result of physical count.

We recommended and Management agreed that, through the, –
Bids and Awards Committee –
familiarize themselves with procurement-related issuances and attend procurement-related seminars to enhance their knowledge about procurement processes;
strictly ensure compliance with the requirements of R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR;
Municipal Accountant –
ensure compliance with the provisions of Manual on the NGAS for LGUs in the recording and recognizing of inventory in the accounting records;
meticulously review and ensure that disbursement vouchers are supported with proper documentation in compliance with relevant rules and regulations before affixing her signature to provide reasonable basis for establishing the validity of claims;
Municipal General Services Officer to comply with Section 121, Volume I, of Manual on the NGAS for LGUs to properly account the issued supplies and materials; and
Municipal Budget Officer comply with the posting and reporting requirements of Item 4.0 of DBM LBC No. 125 dated April 07, 2020.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive to:
instruct the Inventory Committee to submit the RPCPPE for CY 2022 not later than January 31, 2023 to enable reconciliation with the accounting and property records and correction of verified discrepancies;
assign a focal person who will focus on the requirements needed to enable the immediate transfer of title of the subject lands under the name of the Municipality;
instruct the OIC-General Services Officer to –
assign personnel tasked to prepare, complete and maintain updated property cards;
assigning of property numbers to each item in accordance with the uniform identification system for PPE for proper control and monitoring of government property; and
prepare a list for the unfound/missing/stolen items under the Special Education Fund and follow the disposition procedures/guidelines set in the COA Circular 2020-006.
instruct the Disposal Committee to dispose obsolete/unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration of the property and consequent depreciation to its value.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor/Treasurer strategize how to efficiently and effectively collect taxes and consider, among others, the following measures:

Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign; 

Avail of the remedies by administrative action thru levy on real property or by judicial action.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the – 

Inventory Committee to conduct actual physical inventory of the real properties and report their actual conditions through the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE), which shall be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year; 


Management include in the succeeding year’s budget the cost of titling of all untitled/titled lots.

We recommended and Management agreed the following:
Require the GSO to prepare and submit to the Municipal Accountant the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and cause the timely submission of the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued to the Municipal Accountant within five days from month-end, to facilitate the proper recording of transaction and to ensure validated inventory balances and expenses accounts;
Comply strictly to Section 43 of the Manual on the NGAS, for LGUs Volume II, on the preparation by the GSO of the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), to be used by the Accounting Unit as basis in preparing the JEV to record supplies and materials issued;
Require GSO and other supplies/inventory custodians to undertake the actual physical inventory at least once a year and to submit RPCI to the Office of the Auditor not later than January 31 each year.
Enjoin GSO/all inventory custodians and Municipal Accountant to perform the reconciliation of the inventories with the balances in the books of accounts.

We recommended that:
The Inventory Committee headed by General Services Officer:
(a)	Reconcile property records with accounting records and variance shall be traced and investigated immediately;
(b)	Properly classify asset type in conducting physical count and report the same in the RPCPPE per asset type;
(c)	Properly fill out the prescribed RPCPPE format and determine correct unit value per item presented on it.
The Municipal Accountant update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card and reconcile PPE account with the result of physical count.

We reiterated that the Local Chief Executive direct the –
Inventory Team to conduct regular physical count of all properties under the Municipality on a timely basis and submit the prescribed reports to the Audit Team on or before January 31 of each year;

Inventory Committee on Disposal to undertake the proper disposal of unserviceable assets in accordance with applicable rules and regulations on disposal procedure;

Municipal Accountant to make necessary adjustments on the items below the PPE capitalization threshold and the re-computation of annual depreciation on items which did not comply with the prescribed useful life of assets; and

Municipal Accountant, together with the Municipal Treasurer and other personnel involved to complete the maintenance and updating of the required PPELC, RPLC, and Property cards and provide complete and necessary information to facilitate verification and reconciliation.

We recommended and Management agreed that the –

BAC, BAC Secretariat and TWG observe strict compliance with the revised IRR of RA No. 9184 regarding conduct of competitive bidding and evaluate thoroughly the completeness and correctness of bid documents submitted by the bidders to ensure that legally, technically and financially capable contractor/supplier is awarded with the contract;

Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) adhere to the standards and policies set out by the DPWH in the planning and implementation of infrastructure projects;

PMT, in coordination with the BAC and MEO, comply with the requirements under DILG MC No. 2018-61 and 2018-104 in the strict monitoring and implementation of AM Projects;

Municipal Accountant check all the supporting documents attached to the disbursement voucher to determine the validity and correctness of the claim; and ensure that all disbursement vouchers are properly supported with complete documentation required under COA Circular 2012-001, before making any payment.

We recommend that management require the Human Resource Management Office to submit written explanation on the grant of 122 days maternity leave and on the inaction on the employee’s incurrence of immoderate absences.

 We also recommend that management submit the following documents:

1. Original copies of the application for leave filed by the employee in CY 2017;
2. Certified true copy of the Employee’s Leave Card;
3. Original copies of the CY 2017 payroll duly signed by the employee;
4. Duly filled-up Daily Time Record for CY 2017
5. Assumption Letter CY 2018

 Furthermore, we recommend that the human resource management office strictly observe and comply with established laws, rules and regulations concerning personnel movement, and require that application of leave be duly filled-up to provide sufficient details.

We recommended that Management:

Require the business proof of income in the renewal of business permit for the review of the gross receipts/sales declared in the application form that shall be retained by the MTO in the taxpayer’s permanent file for current and future reference;



Include the presumptive income levels to be used in the Presumptive Income Level Assessment Approach in the revision of the Municipal LRC;




Review and ensure that all application forms are properly filled out; and



Include the statement required in Section 6.1.1, illustrated in Annex 1 of Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) - Department of Trade and Industry (DTI)- Department of Information and Communications Technology (DICT) Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 01 in the business permit application form.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to require all AOs to remit daily the full amount collected by them promptly and intact;



Require the Municipal Treasurer to check first the inventory of accountable forms and remittance of cash before issuance of another accountable forms;



Demand from the concerned Collector of Business Tax the missing Official Receipts (ORs) and the remittance of unremitted collections; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to determine the unremitted full amount by the erring collector and to file appropriate legal sanctions, if warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor/Treasurer strategize how to efficiently and effectively collect taxes and consider, among others, the following measures:

Conduct information and education campaign/activities, e.g. social media/radio, and other means of communication to encourage land owners to pay regularly their tax obligation and the benefits of paying early and/or on time. Consider condonation of fines and penalties to delinquent taxpayers;

Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign; 



Avail of the remedies by administrative action thru levy on real property or by judicial action.

