In view of the foregoing audit observations, we have recommended the following:

 That management furnish COA with a copy of any relevant record containing sufficient information about the foregoing receivable balances and exert effort in the collection of said receivables. In the absence of such documents, a request for authority to write-off together with a valid justification may be considered in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005;
 That the breakdown of the beginning balance be prepared and submitted to support the balances of the Due to Officers and Employees account presented in the Financial Statements. Since claimants of terminal leave benefits are no longer connected with the agency, the Accountant is advised to reclassify the benefits accruing to them to the Other Payables account;
 That the amounts set up for Due to Officers and Employees be supported with a copy of duly accomplished disbursement voucher with complete supporting documents to prove that the claim is valid;
 That the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer prepare the necessary disbursement voucher and effect payment/return of the unused portion of funds received to the source agency or request from the agency concerned for authority to use the remaining balance of the account Due to NGAs for other purposes. Meantime, determine the nature of the amount ₱147,309.65 of the Due to NGAs account;
 That schedules to support the beginning balance of Due to LGUs account be prepared and submitted. Prepare the necessary disbursement voucher and effect payment/return the unused portion of funds received from the Provincial Government of Abra amounting to ₱139,637.17;
 That management furnish the COA with a copy of any relevant record containing sufficient information to support the balance of the Other Payables account.

We recommended that Management require:
The Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the updated PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) for Infrastructure Asset accounts to support the GL accounts balance;
The Property Officer - Designate to prepare and maintain the Property Cards per type/category of all the properties owned by the Municipality;
Trace the location and whereabouts of the missing PPE and establish accountability on the personnel entrusted with them. If found unserviceable or with no service potential, must be accordingly dropped from the books through the most appropriate mode of disposal; and

The Municipal Accountant and the GSO/Municipal Treasurer to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted in the reconciliation of PPE records be immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly.

We recommended that Management prepare and issue a well-defined set of policies and guidelines governing the implementation of AICS program which must be aligned with the guidelines issued by the DSWD governing the grants of AICS.  The policies and guidelines may contain the following:

Kind of financial assistance (burial, transportation, medical, educational, food, shelter and others);
Limitations on the amounts given per kind of financial assistance;
Criteria in granting the financial assistance and the documentary requirements for each particular case; and
Well defined roles and responsibilities of the officials processing requests.

We recommended that Management strictly adhere to Sections 22 and 23 of the amendment to Rule XVI of the Omnibus Rules Implementing Book V of EO No. 292 per MC No. 41, s. 1998 on the guidelines on Monetization of Leave Credits.


We also recommended that the HRMO:

Exercise prudence in recommending approval for the grant of leave monetization;

Ensure that officials and employees availing for monetization of vacation leave credits has accumulated no less than 15 days, in which case he can monetize no more than ten days and that five days of vacation leave (VL) credits will remain after monetization which shall be availed only once a year;

Avoid approving monetization of more than 30 days leave credits;

Strictly follow the conditions prescribed in Section 23 of the Omnibus Rules on Leave in case officials and employees chose to avail the special monetization; and

Stop allowing the practice of monetizing sick leave or combination of vacation and sick leave credit balances.

Further, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant check the validity and completeness of the supporting documents before processing any payments for leave monetization.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor/Treasurer strategize how to efficiently and effectively collect taxes and consider, among others, the following measures:

Conduct information and education campaign/activities, e.g. social media/radio, and other means of communication to encourage land owners to pay regularly their tax obligation and the benefits of paying early and/or on time. Consider condonation of fines and penalties to delinquent taxpayers;

Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign; 

Prepare the list of all delinquent real property taxes and submit the same to the Sangguniang Bayan with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection of those taxes; and

Avail of the remedies by administrative action thru levy on real property or by judicial action.

